    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/no-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis QoI validation — CPB operating envelope",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were computed across the five CPB operating points (2.0, 2.5, 3.0, 3.5, and 5.0 L/min at 2000–3500 RPM). Predicted NIH values ranged from 0.003 to 0.021 mg/100 L, consistent with the published range for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump. The Lagrangian power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger coefficients) produced monotonically increasing NIH with rotational speed, confirming the model's ability to rank operating conditions by hemolysis severity. Agreement between replicate simulation runs was within 1.2%, demonstrating numerical repeatability. The assessment team notes that the hemolysis predictions are in line with expected physiological ranges for CPB and that no systematic over- or under-prediction trend was identified across the operating envelope. Validation is considered sufficient to support the worst-case identification claim at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/vad-comparator-mismatch",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Secondary validation against Leverett et al. VAD bench dataset",
      "description": "To further substantiate the hemolysis model, CFD predictions were compared against the Leverett et al. (1993) in-vitro hemolysis dataset, which is widely cited as a benchmark for blood-contacting CFD validation. The Leverett dataset covers flow rates of 6–10 L/min through a rotary blood pump tested under ventricular assist device (VAD) conditions with porcine blood at 37 °C. Predicted NIH values from the present model at equivalent shear-stress exposure levels agreed with the Leverett measurements within 18%, which the assessment team characterizes as acceptable given inter-laboratory variability in hemolysis assays. The comparator dataset is considered well-established and the agreement provides confidence in the power-law model coefficients used in this study. No further qualification of comparator applicability to the CPB flow regime was performed.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/leverett-1993-vad-hemolysis-bench"
    }
  ],
